        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We plan to achieve the highest angular resolution of 0.13" at 330
GHz (Band 7) in the most expanded configuration C34-7.  We can
obtain a better angular resolution at 680 GHz (Band 9), but the
highest frequency observations are limited to the best weather
conditions and suffer from the low atmospheric transmission.  Note
that the proposed angular resolution is still a factor of two better
than or comparable to our CARMA data (0.3" for CI Tau and DL Tau
and 0.13" for HL Tau).  The disks are about 2" in the 1.3 mm continuum
of our CARMA data and the configuration is sensitive up to 2.6",
so we did not expect any significant missing flux issue.

We will set a baseband for 13CO and C18O J=3-2 with a spectral
resolution of about 0.1 km/s and a bandwidth of about 100 km/s and
the other three basebands for continuum, so in total 6 GHz bandwidth
for continuum.  The dual polarization mode is selected for a better
sensitivity.  As far as sensitivity is concerned, we will obtain
at least an order higher S/N than our CARMA images particularly for
imaging substructures.  As shown in the table at the end of Science
Justification, our targets have a peak between 25-38 mJy/beam and
our CARMA data have RMS of about 1-2 mJy/beam at 1.3 mm (230 GHz),
which means 10-40 S/N.  At 330 GHz, we will achieve a noise level
of 0.07 mJy/beam, which provides us 200-1030 S/N.  Note that the
thermal dust continuum of disks is brighter at 330 GHz by a factor
of two than at 230 GHz at least: (330 GHz/230 GHz)^2 ~ 2.1.  This
excellent sensitivity for the extended configuration (C34-7) is
obtained in 3.2 hours including calibrations and overheads, according
to the ALMA OT time estimator: about 26.5 minutes toward each target.
With the observing time, we will achieve 7.1 mJy/beam noise level
corresponding to 4.7 K in a spectral resolution of 0.5 km/s for the
CO isotope lines.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
