        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our project requires multiple wavelength observations.  We plan to
achieve the highest angular resolution of 0.19" at 220 GHz in the
most expanded configuration C34-7.  Note that the proposed angular
resolution best match the Band 7 angular resolution.  The disks are
about 2" in the 1.3 mm continuum of our CARMA data and the configuration
is sensitive up to 4.0", so we did not expect any significant missing
flux issue.

We will set a baseband for 13CO and C18O J=2-1 with a spectral
resolution of about 0.08 km/s and a bandwidth of about 80 km/s and
the other three basebands for continuum, so in total 6 GHz bandwidth
for continuum.  The dual polarization mode is selected for a better
sensitivity.  As far as sensitivity is concerned, we will obtain
at least an order higher S/N than our CARMA images.  As shown in
the table at the end of Science Justification, our targets have a
peak between 25-38 mJy/beam and our CARMA data have RMS of about
1-2 mJy/beam at 1.3 mm (230 GHz), which means 10-40 S/N.  At 220
GHz, we will achieve 0.07 mJy/beam and this noise level provides
us 160-860 S/N.  This excellent sensitivity for the extended
configuration (C34-7) is obtained in 0.7 hour at Band 6 including
calibrations and overheads, according to the ALMA OT time estimator:
about 4.7 minutes toward each target.  With the observing time, we
will achieve 8.8 mJy/beam noise level corresponding to 6.2 K in a
spectral resolution of 0.5 km/s for the CO isotope lines at Band 6.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
